Thailand Stocks: Kim Eng, PTT, PTT Exploration, Sri Trang Agro

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-05-06T10:07:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/thailand-stocks-esso-kim-eng-ptt-exploration-thai-oil.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  Thailand  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4:30 p.m. close in Bangkok.  The SET Index slid 23.02, or 2.1 percent, to 1,050.85, the
most since Feb. 10. The gauge dropped 3.9 percent this week, the
largest weekly decline in April 2010.  Oil companies :  PTT Pcl (PTT)  , Thailand’s biggest energy
company, fell 3.9 percent to 347 baht, the largest decrease
since Jan. 24.  PTT Exploration & Production Pcl (PTTEP)  , the
nation’s only publicly traded oil explorer, lost 4.5 percent to
170.5 baht, the steepest decline since Feb. 10.  Crude oil fell in New York for a fifth day, heading for its
biggest weekly decline since December 2008 after reports
indicated economic weakness in the U.S. and Europe. The contract
yesterday sank 8.6 percent to $99.80 on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange , the lowest settlement since March 16 and the biggest
percentage drop since April 20, 2009.  Kim Eng Securities (Thailand) Pcl (KEST TB), the country’s
largest stock brokerage, jumped 6.9 percent to 15.6 baht, the
biggest gain since Oct. 1. Malayan Banking Bhd., Malaysia’s
biggest lender by assets, offered to buy Kim Eng Securities’
shares it doesn’t already own at 16 baht each, the Thai
brokerage said in a regulatory filing.  Sri Trang Agro-Industry Pcl (STA)  , the biggest publicly
traded rubber producer, lost 4.3 percent to 27.75 baht, the
lowest close since March 22. Rubber futures in Tokyo declined to
its lowest level in seven weeks amid concerns that slowing
economic growth in the U.S. and high prices may reduce demand
for the commodity used in tires.  Thai Airways International Pcl (THAI)  , the country’s
largest carrier, advanced 3.3 percent to 3.9 baht, the most in
two weeks, on expectations lower oil prices will cut its fuel
costs. Crude oil fell as much as 5.2 percent to $94.63 a barrel
in New York trading, while Brent crude oil retreated as much as
5.1 percent to $105.15 a barrel in London.  To contact the reporter on this story:
